I often think that Millennials might be the last generation capable of genuinely appreciating art and forming connections with artists. They don't carry that pressure to view everything through a critical, tinted lens.
We grew up in the golden age of media, when people shared a common understanding of popular culture, but now this collective awareness has disappeared.
At that time, we could immerse ourselves directly without considering the source of the content, because in that era, tracing back to the origins was not easy.
We treat these artists as if they were gods, and there is no reason to question this worship. Thus, we establish a "pseudo-social relationship" with them and regard it as an indispensable part of our lives.
This also explains why we are so fascinated by nostalgia.
While the TV show "The Office" was still airing, my friends and I would gather every Thursday to watch it together, eating pizza as we did so.
This is entirely different from the experience of watching programs through streaming services today. Streaming platforms usually release all 12 episodes at once, allowing everyone to watch at their own pace. When discussing the plot on social media, people often add "spoiler warning" tags, or simply communicate within specific groups.
Subconsciously, we all yearn to relive that sense of collective belonging which connects everyone together.
It's precisely because of our nostalgia that we keep rewatching TV shows like "The Office" or movies like "The Great Debaters," whose memorable catchphrases spread widely online like memes.
We will quote these classic lines from the works and believe that most people can understand the meaning implicitly.
Nowadays, even if something goes viral online, we can't assume that everyone has seen it.
Now that information is exploding, there's simply too much to pay attention to, and it's impossible to simplify... Do we still have a chance to escape this state of information overload?
We keep discovering new media and new artists, only to find that they are either sex offenders with a history of misconduct or stubborn individuals filled with prejudice, and this cycle is endlessly repetitive and tiring.
On one hand, we are immersed in nostalgia, and on the other hand, we are forced to admit that the people who created the art we love may have serious moral flaws. This conflicting mindset leaves us feeling lost and confused.
We will be more careful in establishing "parasocial relationships" with artists.
We gradually realized that it is difficult to ensure one does not harm or exploit others if one wishes to gain wealth and power.
Since the collective consciousness of the media no longer exists, we have developed a class consciousness that helps us maintain critical thinking.
Of course, there are still some people who remain stubbornly misguided, insisting on elevating others to the status of gods. When the idol eventually falls, they pretend to be shocked and horrified.
We are in an era of transformation, and I urgently want to know where we are headed.
Inclusion and safety should be the default.
